{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QoXLnAKe4BxbdBZALVoCT7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the setup. The replica set currently uses internal Kubernetes DNS names. I need to configure split-horizon DNS so MongoDB advertises the external hostnames (domain-rs-1:31181, domain-rs-2:31182, domain-rs-3:31183) to external clients while still using internal addresses internally.\n\nSplit-horizon in MongoDB is configured using the `horizons` field in the replica set member configuration. Each member can have a `horizons` object that maps horizon names to `host:port` strings.\n\nThe approach:\n1. Use `rs.reconfig()` to add `horizons` to each member with the external host:port\n2. The horizon name can be anything (e.g., \"external\") - clients connecting via the external hostnames will get redirected to those addresses\n3. I'll map each member to its corresponding external address and run the reconfiguration from the primary via mongosh in the mongo-client pod\n\nFirst, I need to identify which replica set member is currently the primary.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":664,"cache_read_input_tokens":29515,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":664},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c4b2fc3f-4c0e-454f-8f4a-b6ba64ac3df8","uuid":"6dfbf73e-df4c-4efd-ba54-65ee1c6bbd73","request_id":"req_011CcLJiCafuGEmuqwUzpMLd"}
